The proposed handler puts the use case inside two outer details: `NextRequest`/`NextResponse` and Prisma. That makes the approval rule, invoice calculation, and persistence orchestration harder to test or reuse, and it also leaks ORM shapes into policy. As written, `order: Order` is also the wrong boundary type because the code needs `lines`, which is not part of the plain Prisma `Order` model type.

The smallest production design is one use case with two policy-owned ports and plain DTOs:

```ts
// core/invoicing/create-invoice.ts
export type CreateInvoiceRequest = {
  orderId: string;
};

export type CreateInvoiceResult = {
  invoiceId: string;
  totalCents: number;
};

export type OrderForInvoicing = {
  id: string;
  status: "APPROVED" | "PENDING" | "REJECTED";
  lineAmountsCents: number[];
};

export type InvoiceDraft = {
  orderId: string;
  totalCents: number;
};

export interface LoadOrderForInvoicing {
  load(orderId: string): Promise<OrderForInvoicing | null>;
}

export interface SaveInvoice {
  save(draft: InvoiceDraft): Promise<{ id: string }>;
}

export class OrderNotApprovedError extends Error {}
export class OrderNotFoundError extends Error {}

export class CreateInvoice {
  constructor(
    private readonly loadOrder: LoadOrderForInvoicing,
    private readonly saveInvoice: SaveInvoice,
  ) {}

  async execute(request: CreateInvoiceRequest): Promise<CreateInvoiceResult> {
    const order = await this.loadOrder.load(request.orderId);
    if (!order) throw new OrderNotFoundError();
    if (order.status !== "APPROVED") throw new OrderNotApprovedError();

    const totalCents = order.lineAmountsCents.reduce((sum, amount) => sum + amount, 0);
    const invoice = await this.saveInvoice.save({ orderId: order.id, totalCents });

    return { invoiceId: invoice.id, totalCents };
  }
}
```

Ownership and translation:

- The use case owns `CreateInvoiceRequest`, `CreateInvoiceResult`, `OrderForInvoicing`, `InvoiceDraft`, and the two interfaces.
- The Next.js route translates HTTP into `CreateInvoiceRequest`, calls the use case, then translates result/errors into `NextResponse`.
- The Prisma adapters translate database rows into `OrderForInvoicing` and `InvoiceDraft` into Prisma `create` data.
- Concrete wiring belongs in the outer layer, typically the route module or a small composition function it imports.

```ts
// infrastructure/prisma/prisma-order-loader.ts
export class PrismaOrderLoader implements LoadOrderForInvoicing {
  async load(orderId: string): Promise<OrderForInvoicing | null> {
    const row = await prisma.order.findUnique({
      where: { id: orderId },
      include: { lines: true },
    });
    if (!row) return null;

    return {
      id: row.id,
      status: row.status,
      lineAmountsCents: row.lines.map(line => line.amountCents),
    };
  }
}

// infrastructure/prisma/prisma-invoice-saver.ts
export class PrismaInvoiceSaver implements SaveInvoice {
  async save(draft: InvoiceDraft): Promise<{ id: string }> {
    const row = await prisma.invoice.create({ data: draft });
    return { id: row.id };
  }
}
```

```ts
// app/api/invoices/route.ts
export async function POST(request: NextRequest): Promise<NextResponse> {
  const useCase = new CreateInvoice(
    new PrismaOrderLoader(),
    new PrismaInvoiceSaver(),
  );

  try {
    const result = await useCase.execute({
      orderId: request.nextUrl.searchParams.get("orderId") ?? "",
    });
    return NextResponse.json(
      { id: result.invoiceId, totalCents: result.totalCents },
      { status: 201 },
    );
  } catch (error) {
    if (error instanceof OrderNotFoundError) {
      return NextResponse.json({ error: "order not found" }, { status: 404 });
    }
    if (error instanceof OrderNotApprovedError) {
      return NextResponse.json({ error: "not approved" }, { status: 409 });
    }
    throw error;
  }
}
```

This is the lightest boundary that keeps the approval rule and application action independent from Next.js and Prisma: one focused use case, policy-owned DTOs/ports, humble adapters, and wiring only at the edge.
